KD Practicum 2.3

Recursive vectors

In R, recursive vectors act as containers. Unlike atomic vectors, its contents are not restricted to a single mode and can encompass any data type. Recursive vectors are also called lists, because a list can contain other lists.

We can create lists using the list() function, or coerce other objects with as.list(). Note that each element of this list is named. Names of list elements can be provided as formal parameters to the list() constructor using the = operator.

list(first = list(alpha = 1:5, 
                  beta = 6:10), 
     second = "Hello World!", 
     third = TRUE)
## $first
## $first$alpha
## [1] 1 2 3 4 5
## 
## $first$beta
## [1]  6  7  8  9 10
## 
## 
## $second
## [1] "Hello World!"
## 
## $third
## [1] TRUE

The resulting list comes out as a composition of:

  • another list with two elements (each of which is a vector itself),
  • a character vector,
  • and a single-unit Boolean vector.

Each element of a list starts with name, which can be accessed using the $ sign operator.

The property that makes recursive vectors fundamentally different from atomic vectors is that instead of storing the values itself, they store references to them: l1 <- list(1,2,3)

Like vectors, lists use copy-on-modify behavior; the original list is left unchanged, and R creates a modified copy. This, however, is a shallow copy: the list object and its bindings are copied, but the values pointed to by the bindings are not. The opposite of a shallow copy is a deep copy where the contents of every reference are copied. Prior to R 3.1.0, copies were always deep copies.

Lets explore this behavior on list 1 by:

  • creating a new list l2 <- l1, and
  • changing its second element to 4: l2[[3]] <- 4.

Question 1: What do you think happens and how is this different to copy-on-modify behavior of the atomic vectors? Use tracemem() to find out.

Data frames 1.0

The two most important applications of lists are data frames and tibbles. A data frame is a column-bind list of vectors with attributes for (column) names, row.names, and its class, data.frame. In contrast to a regular list, a data frame has an additional constraint: the length of each of its vectors must be the same. This gives data frames their rectangular structure and explains why they share the properties of both matrices and lists.

  • A data frame has rownames(), colnames(). When names() are used on a data frame then the column names are returned.
  • A data frame has nrow() rows and ncol() columns. dim() returns a vector containing the number of rows and columns.

Note that data frames are column-bound vectors, so copy-on-modify has important consequences when you modify a data frame. Take this data frame as an example: d1 <- data.frame(x = c(1,5,6), y = c(2,4,3)).

If you modify a column, the others will still point to their original references. However, if you modify a row, every column will be modified. This will have severe memory implications if a data frame is large.

d1 <- data.frame(x = c(1,5,6), y = c(2,4,3))
d2 <- d1
# Multiply each value of the second column by 2.
d2[, 2] <- d2[, 2] * 2 
d3 <- d1
# Multiply each value of the first row by 3.
d3[1, ] <- d3[1, ] * 3

Data frames 2.0: tibbles and tribbles

Data frames are one of the biggest and most important ideas in R, and one of the things that make R different from other programming languages. However, in the over 20 years since their creation, the ways that people use R have changed, and some of the design decisions that made sense at the time data frames were created now cause frustration.

This frustration lead to the creation of the tibbles and tribbles, a modern re-imagining of the data frame. They are designed to be (as much as possible) drop-in replacements for data frames that fix those frustrations.

Almost all of the functions that we will use require tibbles, as tibbles are one of the unifying features of the tidyverse. Most other R packages use regular data frames, so we might want to coerce a data frame to a tibble. We can do that with as_tibble():

library(tidyverse)
head(as_tibble(mtcars), 5)
## # A tibble: 5  11
##     mpg   cyl  disp    hp  drat    wt  qsec    vs    am  gear  carb
##   <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1  21       6   160   110  3.9   2.62  16.5     0     1     4     4
## 2  21       6   160   110  3.9   2.88  17.0     0     1     4     4
## 3  22.8     4   108    93  3.85  2.32  18.6     1     1     4     1
## 4  21.4     6   258   110  3.08  3.22  19.4     1     0     3     1
## 5  18.7     8   360   175  3.15  3.44  17.0     0     0     3     2

You can create a new tibble from individual vectors with tibble(). Note that unlike data frames, only single values are recycled.

x <-1:5 ; tibble(x, rnorm(5), TRUE)
## # A tibble: 5  3
##       x `rnorm(5)` `TRUE`
##   <int>      <dbl> <lgl> 
## 1     1     -1.57  TRUE  
## 2     2      0.497 TRUE  
## 3     3      0.204 TRUE  
## 4     4      0.312 TRUE  
## 5     5      1.43  TRUE

Advanced subsetting operators

You have learned basic subsetting operations using the square bracket operator []. However, there are two other subsetting operators: [[ and $. [[ is used for extracting single items, while x$y is a useful shorthand for x[["y"]].

The [[ operator

[[ is most important when working with lists because subsetting a list with [ always returns a smaller list.

Since most ML modelling functions require one or more vector(s) for input, you need to use [[ to extract those from a list, or a data frame. Simple [ wont do the job. The same principle applies on mining ML model objects, which we will learn at week 4.

To help make this easier to understand we can use a metaphor:

If list x is a train carrying objects, then x[[5]] is the object in car 5; x[4:6] is a train of cars 4-6.

Lets use this metaphor to make a simple list:

x <- list(1:3, "a", 4:6)

When extracting a single element, you have two options: you can create a smaller train, i.e., fewer carriages, or you can extract the contents of a particular carriage. This is the difference between [ and [[:

However, because [[ can return only a single item, you must use it with either a single positive integer or a single string. If you use a vector with [[, it will subset recursively, i.e.x[[c(1, 2)]] is equivalent to x[[1]][[2]]. This is a quirky feature that few know about, so I recommend avoiding it in favor of purrr::pluck(), which youll learn about next week.

The $ operator

You should be always using [[ when extracting a specific column or a row from a data frame/tibble for machine learning purposes. Doing so also reinforces the expectation that you are getting and setting individual values.

An alternative way of doing the same thing is using $, which is a shorthand operator: x$y is roughly equivalent to x[["y"]]. Its often used to access variables in a data frame, as in mtcars$cyl or diamonds$carat.

The one important difference between $ and [[ is that $ does (left-to-right) partial matching.

Simplifying and preserving subsetting

Its important to understand the distinction between simplifying and preserving subsetting. - Simplifying subsets returns the simplest possible data structure that can represent the output, and is useful interactively because it usually gives you what you need for ML. - Preserving subsetting keeps the structure of the output the same as the input, and is generally better for programming because the result will always be the same type. - Omitting drop = FALSE when subsetting matrices and data frames is one of the most common sources of programming errors. It will work for your test cases, but then someone will pass in a single column data frame and it will fail in an unexpected and unclear way.

Simplifying Preserving
Vector x[[1]] x[1]
List x[[1]] x[1]
Factor x[1:4, drop = F] x[1:4]
Array x[1, ] or x[,1 ] x[1, , drop = F] or x[,1, drop=F]
Data frame x[,1] or x[[1]] x[,1, drop = F] or x[1]
